<!--
  T1110.001 - Brute Force: Password Guessing (successful logon after pattern)
  Author: Aakash | Date: 2026-05-16

  Detection: a successful Windows logon (4624, authentication_success group)
  from a source IP that also triggered Wazuh's built-in brute-force
  correlation (rule 60204: >=8 auth failures in 240s), within a 5-minute
  window. Catches the post-compromise stage - an attacker who guessed valid
  credentials and is now using them. Fills the gap left by built-in 60204,
  which only ever flags the failures, never the eventual success.

  Composite rule design:
    if_group authentication_success
        -> trigger: any successful Windows logon. NOTE: anchored on the
           GROUP, not if_sid 60106, because SMB/NTLM network logons climb a
           4-rule chain (60106 -> 92651 -> 92652 -> 92657) and end on a rule
           other than 60106. All rules in that chain share the
           authentication_success group, so the group anchor is robust.
    if_matched_sid 60204
        -> precondition: the brute-force correlation must have fired.
    same_field win.eventdata.ipAddress
        -> the success must originate from the brute-forcing IP.
    frequency 2 / timeframe 300
        -> Wazuh forbids frequency=1 (minimum is 2). Requiring >=2 successful
           logons is also higher-confidence: one success after failures may
           be the real user; two+ sessions from a brute-forcing IP is
           unambiguous compromise.

  Filters:
    - Excludes service / loopback source IPs ("-", ::1, 127.0.0.1)
    - Excludes machine accounts (trailing $) and system principals
      (SYSTEM, LOCAL SERVICE, NETWORK SERVICE, ANONYMOUS LOGON, DWM-*, UMFD-*)

  MITRE: T1110.001 (Password Guessing) + T1078 (Valid Accounts).
  Place inside the <group name="local,syslog,sshd,"> block of local_rules.xml.
-->
<rule id="100204" level="14" frequency="2" timeframe="300">
  <if_group>authentication_success</if_group>
  <if_matched_sid>60204</if_matched_sid>
  <same_field>win.eventdata.ipAddress</same_field>
  <field name="win.eventdata.ipAddress" type="pcre2" negate="yes">^-$|^::1$|^127\.0\.0\.1$</field>
  <field name="win.eventdata.targetUserName" type="pcre2" negate="yes">\$$|^SYSTEM$|^LOCAL SERVICE$|^NETWORK SERVICE$|^ANONYMOUS LOGON$|^DWM-|^UMFD-</field>
  <description>Successful Windows logon for $(win.eventdata.targetUserName) from $(win.eventdata.ipAddress) after multiple authentication failures - potential brute force success / credential compromise</description>
  <options>no_full_log</options>
  <mitre>
    <id>T1110.001</id>
    <id>T1078</id>
  </mitre>
  <group>authentication_success,attack,T1110,T1110.001,T1078,brute_force,credential_compromise,</group>
</rule>
